Subject: [PATCH 22/22] Privacy: drop cloudflare-kv observability target from
 default config

Upstream issue: (pai-nix privacy series — no upstream issue; this is a
deliberate distribution-policy divergence, not a bug fix.)

First patch in the pai-nix privacy series. Upstream v5.0.0 ships an
observability target of type "cloudflare-kv" (name "production") in
settings.json by default. That target is the egress sink for four
hooks that fan out work-state and activity to Cloudflare KV:

  - PromptProcessing.hook.ts   (UserPromptSubmit) — pushes state on
                                every prompt submission
  - ToolActivityTracker.hook.ts (PostToolUse)     — tool-activity events
                                (commands run, file paths)
  - ISASync.hook.ts            (PostToolUse)       — work.json on every
                                ISA Write/Edit
  - KVSync.hook.ts             (SessionStart/End)  — work.json snapshots
                                at session boundaries

All four route through observability-transport.ts, which sends a
`sync:work_state` value plus a `sync:events` payload collected from
MEMORY/OBSERVABILITY/*.jsonl (tool-activity + prompt-processing event
streams) to the Cloudflare KV REST API. With the default target
present, the only thing standing between a stock install and
continuous cloud egress of personal activity data is the absence of
CF credentials in ~/.claude/.env — i.e. a stock install starts
leaking the moment a user wires up the dashboard they were nudged to
configure.

pai-nix distribution stance: local-only by default. Removing the
cloudflare-kv target leaves the "local" http target
(http://localhost:31337) in place, so the Pulse dashboard keeps
working in full — it just reads from the local daemon instead of a
cloud key-value store. No code is removed: the `cloudflare-kv` branch
in observability-transport.ts simply has no matching target to act on
and becomes dormant. A user who explicitly wants cloud sync can
re-add the target to settings.json; the capability is preserved,
only the default is flipped from opt-out to opt-in.

This is config-level (settings.json). A follow-up code-level kill
switch in observability-transport.ts (refuse type "cloudflare-kv"
unconditionally) is a candidate for a later patch in the series if
defense-in-depth beyond the shipped default is wanted.

Files touched (paths relative to upstream source root):

  Releases/v5.0.0/.claude/settings.json   :1182-1186

Total: 1 file, 1 hunk, 5 deletions.

Verification: modified settings.json re-parses as valid JSON;
observability.targets contains exactly one entry afterward
({ type: "http", name: "local", url: "http://localhost:31337" }) and
zero entries of type "cloudflare-kv". Hunk generated via `diff -u`
against the upstream v5.0.0 source tree; no hand-counted @@ headers.
